Exercise 1.

Let’s simulate data for a simple linear regression with different errors. First, set \(n = 20\) and \(n=100\). Define \(X\sim U(0,1)\) and \(y=5 + 8X + \epsilon\). Consider try three different options for the errors:

  1. \(\epsilon_i \sim N(0,1)\) , i.e., normal and homoscedastic
  2. \(\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma = 2X_i)\), i.e, normal but heteroscedastic
  3. \(\epsilon_i \sim \chi^2_2 - 2\), i.e., not normal and heteroscedastic.

The task is to examine the assumptions for constant variance and normality. For each case, provide the following

  1. The QQ plot and its interpretation
  2. Plot the residuals vs fitted values and interpret it.

** Answer **

Let’s start with \(n=20\).

 set.seed(12345)
 n <- 20
 x <- runif(n)
 eps1 <- rnorm(n)
 eps2 <- rnorm(n, sd=sqrt(2*x))
 eps3 <- rchisq(n,2)-2
 y1 <- 5 + 8*x + eps1
 y2 <- 5 + 8*x + eps2
 y3 <- 5 + 8*x + eps3
 lmo1 <- lm(y1 ~ x); std.res1 <- rstandard(lmo1)
 lmo2 <- lm(y2 ~ x); std.res2 <- rstandard(lmo2)
 lmo3 <- lm(y3 ~ x); std.res3 <- rstandard(lmo3)
 q1<-car::qqPlot(std.res1); q2<-car::qqPlot(std.res2); q3<-car::qqPlot(std.res3);

 plot(std.res1 ~ fitted(lmo1)); plot(std.res2 ~ fitted(lmo2)); plot(std.res3 ~ fitted(lmo3))

Sample size seems to be too small to see clear trends. In QQ-plot of model 3 results one observation is outside the confidence envelope, which may be expected for residuals skewed to the right. A slight loudspeaker shape is visible in the plot of standardized residuals versus fitted values for model 2 results.

Now let’s try with \(n=200\).

set.seed(6789)
 n <- 100
 x <- runif(n)
 eps1 <- rnorm(n)
 eps2 <- rnorm(n, sd=sqrt(2*x))
 eps3 <- rchisq(n,2)-2
 y1 <- 5 + 8*x + eps1
 y2 <- 5 + 8*x + eps2
 y3 <- 5 + 8*x + eps3
 lmo1 <- lm(y1 ~ x); std.res1 <- rstandard(lmo1)
 lmo2 <- lm(y2 ~ x); std.res2 <- rstandard(lmo2)
 lmo3 <- lm(y3 ~ x); std.res3 <- rstandard(lmo3)
 q1<-car::qqPlot(std.res1); q2<-car::qqPlot(std.res2); q3<-car::qqPlot(std.res3);

 plot(std.res1 ~ fitted(lmo1)); plot(std.res2 ~ fitted(lmo2)); plot(std.res3 ~ fitted(lmo3))

Patterns are much more clear now. Model 1 results looks ok. Model 2 results shows evident “loudspeaker shape” in plot of residuals versus fitted values. Many observations outside the confidence envelope in QQ-plot. Model 3 results shows distinctive skewness to the right in normal QQ-plot; asymmetry of distribution can also be seen in plot of residuals versus fitted values; many observations are outside the confidence envelope in QQ-plot. The largest standardized residual is even larger than 4.

Exercise 2.

Experimenting with component-plus-residual plots:

Generate random samples of 100 observations according to each of the schemes below. In each case, construct the component-plus-residual plots for \(X_1\) and \(X_2\). Do these plots accurately capture the partial relationships between \(Y\) and each of \(X_1\) and \(X_2\)? Whenever they appear, \(\epsilon\) and \(\delta\) are N(0; 1) and independent of each other and of the other variables. You can use the command crPlot() from the car package.

Choose any three cases to do in the classroom. Try the others at home.

  1. Independent \(X's\) and a linear regression: \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) independent and uniformly distributed on the interval [0; 1], and \(Y = X_1 + X_2 + 0.1\epsilon\).

  2. Linearly related \(Xs\) and a linear regression: \(X_1\) uniformly distributed on the interval [0; 1], \(X_2 = X_1 + 0.1\delta\) and \(Y = X_1 + X_2 + 0.1\epsilon\).

  3. Independent \(Xs\) and a nonlinear regression on one \(X\): \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) independent and uniformly distributed on interval [0; 1]; \(Y = 2(X_1 - 0.5)^2 + X_2 + 0.1\epsilon\).

  4. Linearly related \(Xs\) and a nonlinear regression on one \(X\): \(X_1\) uniformly distributed on the interval [0; 1], \(X_2 = X_1 + 0.1\delta\); \(Y = 2(X_1 - 0.5)^2 + X_2 + 0.1\epsilon\).

  5. Nonlinearly related \(X's\) and a linear regression: \(X_1\) uniformly distributed on the interval [0; 1]; \(X_2 = |X_1 - 0.5|\); \(Y = X_1 + X_2 + 0.02\epsilon\).

  6. Nonlinearly related \(X's\) and a linear regression on one \(X\): \(X_1\) uniformly distributed on the interval [0; 1]; \(X_2 = |X1 - 0.5|\); \(Y = 2(X_1 - 0.5)^2 + X_2 + 0.02\epsilon\).

Answer

 X1 <- runif(100)
 X2 <- runif(100)
 epsilon <- rnorm(100)
 Y <- X1 + X2 + 0.1*epsilon
 lmo.a <- lm(Y ~ X1 + X2)
 crPlot(lmo.a,X1) # function from car library

 crPlot(lmo.a,X2)

Plots look OK. No indication of deviation from linearity, as expected.

You can also do the same manually, without any fancy smoothers.

res <- residuals(lmo.a)
respluscomp1 <- residuals(lmo.a) + coef(lmo.a)[2]*X1
respluscomp2 <- residuals(lmo.a) + coef(lmo.a)[3]*X2
plot(respluscomp1 ~ X1)

plot(respluscomp2 ~ X2)

Notice that crplot() gives y-axis centered around 0, so it uses centered regressors to construct “residual-plus-component”, whereas we use below the original not-centered regressor.

 X1 <- runif(100)
 delta <- rnorm(100)
 epsilon <- rnorm(100)
 X2 <- X1 + 0.1*delta
 Y <- X1 + X2 + 0.1*epsilon
 lmo.b <- lm(Y ~ X1 + X2)
 crPlot(lmo.b,X1)

 crPlot(lmo.b,X2)

Plots look largely same as in case of independent regressors. Standard error of coefficients is larger now, but this is not visible in plot.

 X1 <- runif(100)
 X2 <- runif(100)
 epsilon <- rnorm(100)
 Y <- 2*(X1-0.5)^2 + X2 + 0.1*epsilon
 lmo.c <- lm(Y ~ X1 + X2)
 crPlot(lmo.c,X1)

 crPlot(lmo.c,X2)

Nonlinearity in plot versus \(X_1\) is obvious.

 X1 <- runif(100)
 delta <- rnorm(100)
 X2 <- X1 + 0.1*delta
 epsilon <- rnorm(100)
 Y <- 2*(X1-0.5)^2 + X2 + 0.1*epsilon
 lmo.d <- lm(Y ~ X1 + X2)
 crPlot(lmo.d,X1)

 crPlot(lmo.d,X2)

Again, nonlinearity in plot versus \(X_1\) is obvious. The “leakage” from \(X_1\) to \(X_2\) indeed is visible: there appears to be non-linearity in the relationship of \(Y\) with \(X_2\) as well.

 X1 <- runif(100)
 X2 <- abs(X1 - 0.5)
 epsilon <- rnorm(100)
 Y <- X1 + X2 + 0.02*epsilon
 lmo.e <- lm(Y ~ X1 + X2)
 crPlot(lmo.e,X1)

 crPlot(lmo.e,X2)

Plots look OK.

 X1 <- runif(100)
 X2 <- abs(X1 - 0.5)
 epsilon <- rnorm(100)
 Y <- 2*(X1-0.5)^2 + X2 + 0.02*epsilon
 lmo.f <- lm(Y ~ X1 + X2)
 crPlot(lmo.f,X1)

 crPlot(lmo.f,X2)

Nonlinearity in partial relationship of \(Y\) with \(X_1\) is visible.

Exercise 3

Recall the Savings data that we have seen during the lecture. Perform Box-Cox transformation on the datausing boxcox() command from MASS package.

  1. Plot the log-likelihood vs lambda. Indicate the confidence interval provided by the plot (you need to narrow the range of lambda to make it visible, see the code).

  2. Give the estimated lambda (i.e., the one that maximizes the log-likelihood).

  3. Which test do you need to consider to check if the response of the savingsneeds a transformation?

  4. Look at your confidence interval. Do you reject or fail to reject the test in c)?

** Answer **

data(savings)
head(savings)
##              sr pop15 pop75     dpi ddpi
## Australia 11.43 29.35  2.87 2329.68 2.87
## Austria   12.07 23.32  4.41 1507.99 3.93
## Belgium   13.17 23.80  4.43 2108.47 3.82
## Bolivia    5.75 41.89  1.67  189.13 0.22
## Brazil    12.88 42.19  0.83  728.47 4.56
## Canada     8.79 31.72  2.85 2982.88 2.43
g <- lm(sr ~ pop15+pop75+dpi+ddpi,savings)
summary(g)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = sr ~ pop15 + pop75 + dpi + ddpi, data = savings)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -8.2422 -2.6857 -0.2488  2.4280  9.7509 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 28.5660865  7.3545161   3.884 0.000334 ***
## pop15       -0.4611931  0.1446422  -3.189 0.002603 ** 
## pop75       -1.6914977  1.0835989  -1.561 0.125530    
## dpi         -0.0003369  0.0009311  -0.362 0.719173    
## ddpi         0.4096949  0.1961971   2.088 0.042471 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 3.803 on 45 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3385, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2797 
## F-statistic: 5.756 on 4 and 45 DF,  p-value: 0.0007904
bc <- boxcox(g,plotit=T)

#We can narrow the range of lambda, to make it more visible
bc <- boxcox(g,plotit=T,lambda=seq(0.5,1.5,by=0.1))

# Exact lambda
lambda <- bc$x[which.max(bc$y)]
lambda
## [1] 0.9545455

The first plot is too broad. We can narrow the range of \(\lambda\) in the second plot so that we can read off the confidence interval more easily. The estimate of \(\lambda\) is 0.954. The confidence interval for \(\lambda\) runs from about 0.6 to about 1.4. To check if we need a transformation, we need to conduct the following test: \(H_0: \lambda=1\) vs \(H_0: \lambda\not = 1\). We can see that there is no good reason to transform, because the confidence interval includes 1.

Exercise 4

Let’s look at an example concerning the number of species of tortoise on the various Galapagos Islands. There are 30 cases (Islands) and 7 variables in the dataset gala. The variables are

  • Species: The number of species of tortoise found on the island
  • Endemics: The number of endemic species
  • Elevation: The highest elevation of the island
  • Nearest: The distance from the nearest island (km)
  • Scruz: The distance from Santa Cruz island (km)
  • Adjacent: The area of the adjacent island (km2)

  1. Regress Species against all the other variables. Provide the summary of the model. What is the \(R^2\) of the model.

  2. Provide the QQ-plot of the response variable. What is your opinion?

  3. Perform Box-Cox transformation and provide the results. Does the response in the gala data need transformation?

  4. Perform the Box-Cox transoformation on the response variable. Provide the QQ-plot of the response variable again after the transformation. Discuss the results.

Exercise 5

The aatemp data come from U.S. Historical Climatology network. They are the annual mean temperatures (in degrees F) in Ann Arbor, Michigan, going back about 150 year.

  1. Regress the temperature against the year. Check the scatterplot temp vs year. Provide the \(R^2\). Is there a linear trend?

  2. Fit a polynomial model with degree 10. Provide the summary. What is the \(R^2\)? Is the model fit better with the polynomial?

  3. Sequentially reduce the degree of the model (of degree 9, 8, etc.). Stop until the highest order term is significant. Which is the order of that model? What is the \(R^2\)?

  4. Plot your fitted model (i.e., the curve) over the scatterplot of the data. Use this model to predict the temperature in 2020. Use predict() function (check the description in R).

For the orthogonal polynomials, we use the function poly(). Because the different terms are orthogonal, the sums of squares are not order dependent. So, we may look at the output from the order 10 polynomial to see which terms can be dropped. P-values will change only a bit if you would actually remove the terms, because the denominator of the F-statistics (or t-statistics) change slightly.

  1. (Optional) Suppose someone claims that the temperature was constant until 1930 and then began a linear trend. In this situation, we could of fitting two regression models (before 1930 and after), however, the regression function won’t be continous. Instead, one can use broken stick regression, or more generally called segmented regression or piecewise regression. Define two basis functions:

\[\begin{gather*} B_L(x)= \begin{cases} c - x & \text{if} x<c\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} \end{gather*}\] and

\[\begin{gather*} B_R(x)= \begin{cases} x - c & \text{if} x > c\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} \end{gather*}\]

Next, fit linear regression model \(Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 B_L(X) + \beta_2 B_R(X) + \epsilon\). Two regression lines are guaranteed to meet at \(c\) (why?). Regression function is continuous now. Fit a model corresponding to this claim using brokenstick() function. What does the fitted model say about this claim? Also, plot the ordinary linear model obtained in a). Compare the results.

  1. (Optional) Make a cubic spline fit with 6 basis functions evenly spaced on the range. Plot the fit in comparison to the previous fits. Does this model fit better than the straight line model? You can check this with the anova() function.

# First, let's run two regression models, befor and after 1930 (not needed)
  g1 <- lm(temp ~ year, aatemp, subset=(year<1930))
  g2 <- lm(temp ~ year, aatemp, subset=(year>=1930))
  plot(aatemp$year, aatemp$temp, xlab="Year", ylab="temp")
  abline(v=1930, lty=5)
  range(aatemp$year)
## [1] 1854 2000
  segments(1850, g1$coef[1]+g1$coef[2]*1850, 1930, g1$coef[1]+g1$coef[2]*1930, lty=2)
  segments(2010, g2$coef[1]+g2$coef[2]*2010, 1930, g2$coef[1]+g2$coef[2]*1930, lty=2)
  
  #Now, let's use broken stick regression
  lhs <- function(x) ifelse(x<1930, 1930-x, 0) # not needed
  rhs <- function(x) ifelse(x<1930, 0, x-1930)
  brokenstick <- lm(temp ~ rhs(year), aatemp)
  summary(brokenstick)

The fitted model has \(R^2 =0.0546\) whereas ordinary linear regression has \(R^2 =0.0845\). Both models contain 2 regression coefficients. The lower \(R^2\) of the broken stick model is not very promising.
